{"model": "Qwen 3.5 9B", "runtime": "llamacpp", "prompt_name": "math_combinatorics__t3_cot", "prompt_tokens": 0, "generation_tokens": 0, "prompt_tps": 540.7, "generation_tps": 1.7, "peak_memory_gb": 0.0, "wall_time_sec": 28.2, "output": "To find the number of ways to choose 3 items from a set of 7, we use the combination formula because the order of selection does not matter. The formula for combinations is:\n\n$$C(n, k) = \\frac{n!}{k!(n - k)!}$$\n\nWhere:\n*   $n$ is the total number of items (7).\n*   $k$ is the number of items to choose (3).\n*   $!$ denotes a factorial (e.g., $3! = 3 \\times 2 \\times 1$).\n\nStep 1: Substitute the values into the formula.\n$$C(7, 3) = \\frac{7!}{3!(7 - 3)!}$$\n\nStep 2: Simplify the denominator.\n$$C(7, 3) = \\frac{7!}{3! \\times 4!}$$\n\nStep 3: Expand the factorials.\n$$7! = 7 \\times 6 \\times 5 \\times 4!$$\n$$3! = 3 \\times 2 \\times 1 = 6$$\n$$4! = 4 \\times 3 \\times 2 \\times 1$$\n\nSo the expression becomes:\n$$C(7, 3) = \\frac{7 \\times 6 \\times 5 \\times 4!}{6 \\times 4!}$$\n\nStep 4: Cancel out common terms ($4!$ and the 6).\n$$C(7, 3) = \\frac{7 \\times 6 \\times 5}{6}$$\n$$C(7, 3) = 7 \\times 5$$\n\nStep 5: Calculate the final product.\n$$7 \\times 5 = 35$$\n\nThere are 35 ways to choose 3 items from a set of 7.\n\nANSWER: 35", "error": null, "prompt_hash": "0906c375ac54"}
